Here's a function in JavaScript that checks if any of the numbers in an array is a prime number and prints the prime number to the console if found:
```javascript
function isPrime(array) {
  for (let i = 0; i < array.length; i++) {
    let isPrime = true;
    for (let j = 2; j < array[i]; j++) {
      if (array[i] % j === 0) {
        isPrime = false;
        break;
      }
    }
    if (isPrime) {
      console.log(array[i]);
      return array[i];
    }
  }
  return null;
}

// Example usage:
const numbers = [11, 13, 17, 19, 23];
const primeNumber = isPrime(numbers);

if (primeNumber !== null) {
  console.log(`The first prime number in the array is: ${primeNumber}`);
} else {
  console.log("The array does not contain any prime numbers.");
}
```
This function iterates through the array and checks if each number is a prime number by testing divisibility with numbers from 2 to the square root of the number. If it finds a number that divides the current number, the number is not prime. Otherwise, it logs the prime number to the console.

